# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nats-messaging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] An **enterprise messaging system** (**EMS**) or messaging system in brief is a set of published enterprise-wide standards that allows organizations to send semantically precise messages between computer systems.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] EMS systems promote loosely coupled architectures that allow changes in the formats of messages to have minimum impact on message subscribers.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] EMS systems are facilitated by the use of structured messages (such as using XML or JSON), and appropriate protocols, such as DDS, MSMQ, AMQP or SOAP with web services.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] *Routing*: Messages need to be routed efficiently from the sender to the receiver.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] Intermediate nodes may need to route the messages if the body of the message is encrypted.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] *Metadata*: The body of the document contains information that must be unambiguously interpreted.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] Metadata registries should be used to create precise definitions for each data element.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] *Subscription*: Systems should be able to subscribe to all messages that match a specific pattern.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] Messages with a specific content may be routed differently.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] For example, some messages may have different priority or security policies.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] *Policy*: Enterprise messaging systems should provide some consideration for a centralized policy of messages such as what classes or roles of users can access different fields of any message.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] *Message body semantics* – Message body semantics include the precise definition of all of the data elements in the body of the message.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] Message semantics can be aided by the use of a precise data dictionary that documents metadata.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] The commonalities between messaging systems (in terms of capabilities and architecture) have been captured in a platform-independent fashion as enterprise integration patterns (a.k.a. messaging patterns).
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] Note that an Enterprise Messaging System should not be confused with an electronic mail system used for delivering human readable text messages to individual people.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] An example of a specific application programming interface (API) that implements an enterprise messaging system is the Java Message Service.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] Although this is an API it embodies many of the same issues involved in setting up a full EMS.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] Policy statements may also be extracted from a centralized policy server.
[src:nats-messaging/enterprise-messaging-system] These policy statements can be expressed in the XML Access Control Markup Language (XACML).
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] An *event* can be defined as "a significant change in state".
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] For example, when a consumer purchases a car, the car's state changes from "for sale" to "sold".
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] A car dealer's system architecture may treat this state change as an event whose occurrence can be made known to other applications within the architecture.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] From a formal perspective, what is produced, published, propagated, detected or consumed is a (typically asynchronous) message called the event notification, and not the event itself, which is the state change that triggered the message emission.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] However, the term *event* is often used metonymically to denote the notification message itself, which may lead to some confusion.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This is due to Event-driven architectures often being designed atop **message-driven architectures**, where such a communication pattern requires one of the inputs to be text-only, the message, to differentiate how each communication should be handled.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This architectural pattern may be applied by the design and implementation of applications and systems that transmit events among loosely coupled software components and services.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven system typically consists of event emitters (or agents), event consumers (or sinks), and event channels.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Emitters have the responsibility to detect, gather, and transfer events.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] An Event Emitter does not know the consumers of the event, it does not even know if a consumer exists, and in case it exists, it does not know how the event is used or further processed.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Sinks have the responsibility of applying a reaction as soon as an event is presented.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The reaction might or might not be completely provided by the sink itself.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] For instance, the sink might just have the responsibility to filter, transform and forward the event to another component or it might provide a self-contained reaction to such an event.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Event channels are conduits in which events are transmitted from event emitters to event consumers.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The knowledge of the correct distribution of events is exclusively present within the event channel.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The physical implementation of event channels can be based on traditional components such as message-oriented middleware or point-to-point communication which might require a more appropriate transactional executive framework.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Building systems around an event-driven architecture simplifies horizontal scalability in distributed computing models and makes them more resilient to failure.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This is because application state can be copied across multiple parallel snapshots for high-availability.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] New events can be initiated anywhere, but more importantly propagate across the network of data stores updating each as they arrive.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Adding extra nodes becomes trivial as well: you can simply take a copy of the application state, feed it a stream of events and run with it.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architecture can complement service-oriented architecture (SOA) because services can be activated by triggers fired on incoming events.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This paradigm is particularly useful whenever the sink does not provide any self-contained executive.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] SOA 2.0 evolves the implications SOA and EDA architectures provide to a richer, more robust level by leveraging previously unknown causal relationships to form a new event pattern.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This new business intelligence pattern triggers further autonomous human or automated processing that adds exponential value to the enterprise by injecting value-added information into the recognized pattern which could not have been achieved previously.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture has two primary topologies.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] With “broker topology”, components broadcast events to the entire system without any orchestrator.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides higher performance and scalability.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] With “mediator topology”, there is a central orchestrator which controls workflow of events.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides better control and error handling capabilities.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] You can also use a hybrid model and combine these two topologies.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] There are different types of events in EDA, and opinions on their classification may vary.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Domain events signify important occurrences within a specific business domain.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] These events are restricted to a bounded context and are vital for preserving business logic.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Typically, domain events have lighter payloads, containing only the necessary information for processing.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This is because event listeners are generally within the same service, where their requirements are more clearly understood.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] On the other hand, integration events serve to communicate changes across different bounded contexts.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] They are crucial for ensuring data consistency throughout the entire system.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Integration events tend to have more complex payloads with additional attributes, as the needs of potential listeners can differ significantly.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This often leads to a more thorough approach to communication, resulting in overcommunication to ensure that all relevant information is effectively shared.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] An event can be made of two parts, the event header and the event body also known as event payload.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The event header might include information such as event name, time stamp for the event, and type of event.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The event payload provides the details of the state change detected.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] An event body should not be confused with the pattern or the logic that may be applied in reaction to the occurrence of the event itself.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This method involves including only keys or IDs, allowing consumers to fetch the required data from external data sources, such as databases.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] While this approach is less scalable and slower due to the need for database queries, it minimizes bandwidth usage and reduces coupling issues.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] These methods represent two ends of a spectrum rather than binary choices.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Architects must carefully size the event payloads to meet the specific needs of event consumers.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] In event driven architectures, event evolution poses challenges, such as managing inconsistent event schemas across services and ensuring compatibility during gradual system updates.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Event evolution strategies in event-driven architectures (EDA) can ensure that systems can handle changes to events without disruption.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] These strategies can include versioning events, such as semantic versioning or schema evolution, to maintain backward and forward compatibility.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Adapters can translate events between old and new formats, ensuring consistent processing across components.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] These techniques can enable systems to evolve while remaining compatible and reliable in complex, distributed environments.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The first logical layer is the event producer, which senses a fact and represents that fact as an event message.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] As an example, an event producer could be an email client, an E-commerce system, a monitoring agent or some type of physical sensor.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Converting the data collected from such a diverse set of data sources to a single standardized form of data for evaluation is a significant task in the design and implementation of this first logical layer.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] However, considering that an event is a strongly declarative frame, any informational operations can be easily applied, thus eliminating the need for a high level of standardization.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] An event channel is a mechanism of propagating the information collected from an event generator to the event engine or sink.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This could be a TCP/IP connection, or any type of an input file (flat, XML format, e-mail, etc.).
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Several event channels can be opened at the same time.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Usually, because the event processing engine has to process them in near real time, the event channels will be read asynchronously.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The events are stored in a queue, waiting to be processed later by the event processing engine.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The event processing engine is the logical layer responsible for identifying an event, and then selecting and executing the appropriate reaction.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] It can also trigger a number of assertions.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] For example, if the event that comes into the event processing engine is a product ID low in stock, this may trigger reactions such as “Order product ID” and “Notify personnel”.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This is the logical layer where the consequences of the event are shown.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This can be done in many different ways and forms; e.g., an email is sent to someone and an application may display some kind of warning on the screen.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Depending on the level of automation provided by the sink (event processing engine) the downstream activity might not be required.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] There are three general styles of event processing: simple, stream, and complex.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The three styles are often used together in a mature event-driven architecture.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing concerns events that are directly related to specific, measurable changes of condition.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] In simple event processing, a notable event happens which initiates downstream action(s).
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of work, thereby reducing lag time and cost.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] For example, simple events can be created by a sensor detecting changes in tire pressures or ambient temperature.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The car's tire incorrect pressure will generate a simple event from the sensor that will trigger a yellow light advising the driver about the state of a tire.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] In event stream processing (ESP), both ordinary and notable events happen.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Ordinary events (orders, RFID transmissions) are screened for notability and streamed to information subscribers.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Event stream processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of information in and around the enterprise, which enables in-time decision making.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing (CEP) allows patterns of simple and ordinary events to be considered to infer that a complex event has occurred.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing evaluates a confluence of events and then takes action.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The events (notable or ordinary) may cross event types and occur over a long period of time.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The event correlation may be causal, temporal, or spatial.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] CEP requires the employment of sophisticated event interpreters, event pattern definition and matching, and correlation techniques.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] CEP is commonly used to detect and respond to business anomalies, threats, and opportunities.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Online event processing (OLEP) uses asynchronous distributed event logs to process complex events and manage persistent data.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] OLEP allows reliably composing related events of a complex scenario across heterogeneous systems.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] It thereby enables very flexible distribution patterns with high scalability and offers strong consistency.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] However, it cannot guarantee upper bounds on processing time.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven architecture is extremely loosely coupled and well distributed.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The great distribution of this architecture exists because an event can be almost anything and exist almost anywhere.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The architecture is extremely loosely coupled because the event itself doesn't know about the consequences of its cause. e.g.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] If we have an alarm system that records information when the front door opens, the door itself doesn't know that the alarm system will add information when the door opens, just that the door has been opened.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architectures have loose coupling within space, time and synchronization, providing a scalable infrastructure for information exchange and distributed workflows.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] However, event-architectures are tightly coupled, via event subscriptions and patterns, to the semantics of the underlying event schema and values.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] The high degree of semantic heterogeneity of events in large and open deployments such as smart cities and the sensor web makes it difficult to develop and maintain event-based systems.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] In order to address semantic coupling within event-based systems the use of approximate semantic matching of events is an active area of research.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture is susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Finding the right balance in the number of events can be quite difficult.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Generating too many detailed events can overwhelm the system, making it hard to analyze the overall event flow effectively.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This challenge becomes even greater when rollbacks are required.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Conversely, if events are overly consolidated, it can lead to unnecessary processing and responses from event consumers.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] To achieve an optimal balance, Mark Richards recommends to consider the impact of each event and whether consumers need to review the event payloads to determine their actions.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] For instance, in a compliance check scenario, it may be adequate to publish just two types of events: compliant and non-compliant.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] This method ensures that each event is only processed by the relevant consumers, reducing unnecessary workload.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] One of the challenges of using event driven architecture is error handling.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] One way to address this issue is to use a separate error-handler processor.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] So, when the event consumer experiences an error, it immediately and asynchronously sends the erroneous event to the error-handler processor and moves on.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Error-handler processor tries to fix the error and sends the event back to the original channel.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] But if the error-handler processor fails, then it can send the erroneous event to an administrator for further inspection.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Note that if you use an error-handler processor, erroneous events will be processed out of sequence when they are resubmitted.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] Another challenge of using event driven architecture is data loss.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] If any of the components crashes before successfully processing and handing over the event to its next component, then the event is dropped and never makes it into the final destination.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] To minimize the chance of data loss, you can persist in-transit events and remove / dequeue the events only when the next component has acknowledged the receipt of the event.
[src:nats-messaging/event-driven-architecture] These features are usually known as "client acknowledge mode" and "last participant support".
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] A **message broker** (also known as an **integration broker** or **interface engine**) is an intermediary computer program module that translates a message from the formal messaging protocol of the sender to the formal messaging protocol of the receiver.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] Message brokers are elements in telecommunication or computer networks where software applications communicate by exchanging formally defined messages.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] Message brokers are a building block of message-oriented middleware (MOM) but are typically not a replacement for traditional middleware like MOM and remote procedure call (RPC).
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] A message broker is an architectural pattern for message validation, transformation, and routing.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] It mediates communication among applications, minimizing the mutual awareness that applications should have of each other in order to be able to exchange messages, effectively implementing decoupling.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] The primary purpose of a broker is to take incoming messages from applications and perform some action on them.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] Message brokers can decouple end-points, meet specific non-functional requirements, and facilitate reuse of intermediary functions.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] For example, a message broker may be used to manage a workload queue or message queue for multiple receivers, providing reliable storage, guaranteed message delivery and perhaps transaction management.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] Message brokers are generally based on one of two fundamental architectures: hub-and-spoke and message bus.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] In the first, a central server acts as the mechanism that provides integration services, whereas with the latter, the message broker is a communication backbone or distributed service that acts on the bus.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] Additionally, a more scalable multi-hub approach can be used to integrate multiple brokers.
[src:nats-messaging/message-broker] Message brokers that are purpose built to achieve time-bounded communications with end-to-end predictability allow for the development of real-time systems that require execution predictability.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] MOM allows application modules to be distributed over heterogeneous platforms and reduces the complexity of developing applications that span multiple operating systems and network protocols.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The middleware creates a distributed communications layer that insulates the application developer from the details of the various operating systems and network interfaces.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Application programming interfaces (APIs) that extend across diverse platforms and networks are typically provided by MOM.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] This middleware layer allows software components (applications, servlets, and other components) that have been developed independently and might run on different networked platforms to interact with one another.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Applications distributed on different network nodes use the application interface to communicate.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, by providing an administrative interface, this new, virtual system of interconnected applications can be made fault tolerant and secure.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] MOM provides software elements that reside in all communicating components of a client/server architecture and typically support asynchronous calls between the client and server applications.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] MOM reduces the involvement of application developers with the complexity of the master-slave nature of the client/server mechanism.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] All these models make it possible for one software component to affect the behavior of another component over a network.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] They are different in that RPC- and ORB-based middleware create systems of tightly coupled components, whereas MOM-based systems allow for a loose coupling of components.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In an RPC- or ORB-based system, when one procedure calls another, it must wait for the called procedure to return before it can do anything else.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In these mostly synchronous messaging models, the middleware functions partly as a super-linker, locating the called procedure on a network and using network services to pass function or method parameters to the procedure and then to return results.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Note that Object request brokers also support fully asynchronous messaging via oneway invocations.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Central reasons for using a message-based communications protocol include its ability to store (buffer), route, or transform messages while conveying them from senders to receivers.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Another advantage of messaging provider-mediated messaging between clients is that by adding an administrative interface, you can monitor and tune performance.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Client applications are thus effectively relieved of every problem except that of sending, receiving, and processing messages.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] It is up to the code that implements the MOM system and up to the administrator to resolve issues like interoperability, reliability, security, scalability, and performance.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Using a MOM system, a client makes an API call to send a message to a destination managed by the provider.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The call invokes provider services to route and deliver the message.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Once it has sent the message, the client can continue to do other work, confident that the provider retains the message until a receiving client retrieves it.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The message-based model, coupled with the mediation of the provider, makes it possible to create a system of loosely coupled components.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] MOM comprises a category of inter-application communication software that generally relies on asynchronous message-passing, as opposed to a request-response architecture.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In asynchronous systems, message queues provide temporary storage when the destination program is busy or not connected.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, most asynchronous MOM systems provide persistent storage to back up the message queue.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] This means that the sender and receiver do not need to connect to the network at the same time (asynchronous delivery), and problems with intermittent connectivity are solved.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] It also means that should the receiver application fail for any reason, the senders can continue unaffected, as the messages they send will simply accumulate in the message queue for later processing when the receiver restarts.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Many message-oriented middleware implementations depend on a message queue system.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations permit routing logic to be provided by the messaging layer itself, while others depend on client applications to provide routing information or allow for a mix of both paradigms.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations make use of broadcast or multicast distribution paradigms.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In a message-based middleware system, the message received at the destination need not be identical to the message originally sent.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] A MOM system with built-in intelligence can transform messages and route to match the requirements of the sender or of the recipient.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In conjunction with the routing and broadcast/multicast facilities, one application can send a message in its own native format, and two or more other applications may each receive a copy of the message in their own native format.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Many modern MOM systems provide sophisticated message transformation (or mapping) tools which allow programmers to specify transformation rules applicable to a simple GUI drag-and-drop operation.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The primary disadvantage of many message-oriented middleware systems is that they require an extra component in the architecture, the message transfer agent (message broker).
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] As with any system, adding another component can lead to reductions in performance and reliability, and can also make the system as a whole more difficult and expensive to maintain.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, many inter-application communications have an intrinsically synchronous aspect, with the sender specifically wanting to wait for a reply to a message before continuing (see real-time computing and near-real-time for extreme cases).
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Because message-based communication inherently functions asynchronously, it may not fit well in such situations.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] That said, most MOM systems have facilities to group a request and a response as a single pseudo-synchronous transaction.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] With a synchronous messaging system, the calling function does not return until the called function has finished its task.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In a loosely coupled asynchronous system, the calling client can continue to load work upon the recipient until the resources needed to handle this work are depleted and the called component fails.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Of course, these conditions can be minimized or avoided by monitoring performance and adjusting message flow, but this is work that is not needed with a synchronous messaging system.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The important thing is to understand the advantages and liabilities of each kind of system.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Each system is appropriate for different kinds of tasks.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Sometimes, a combination of the two kinds of systems is required to obtain the desired behavior.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Historically, there was a lack of standards governing the use of message-oriented middleware that has caused problems.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Most of the major vendors have their own implementations, each with its own application programming interface (API) and management tools.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] One of the long-standing standards for message-oriented middleware is X/Open group's XATMI specification (Distributed Transaction Processing: The XATMI Specification) which standardizes API for interprocess communications.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Known implementations for this API is ATR Baltic's Enduro/X middleware and Oracle's Tuxedo.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) is an approved OASIS and ISO standard that defines the protocol and formats used between participating application components, so implementations are interoperable.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] It also supports transaction management, queuing, distribution, security, management, clustering, federation and heterogeneous multi-platform support.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Java applications that use AMQP are typically written in Java JMS.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Other implementations provide APIs for C#, C++, PHP, Python, Ruby, and other programming languages.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The High Level Architecture (HLA IEEE 1516) is an Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) and Simulation Interoperability Standards Organization (SISO) standard for simulation interoperability.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] It defines a set of services, provided through an API in C++ or Java.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The services offer publish/subscribe-based information exchange, based on a modular Federation Object Model.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] There are also services for coordinated data exchange and time advance, based on logical simulation time, as well as synchronization points.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Additional services provide transfer of ownership, data distribution optimizations and monitoring and management of participating Federates (systems).
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The MQ Telemetry Transport (MQTT) is an ISO standard (ISO/IEC PRF 20922) supported by the OASIS organization.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] It provides a lightweight publish/subscribe reliable messaging transport protocol on top of TCP/IP suitable for communication in M2M/IoT contexts where a small code footprint is required and/or network bandwidth is at a premium.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The Object Management Group's Data Distribution Service (DDS) provides message-oriented Publish/Subscribe (P/S) middleware standard that aims to enable scalable, real-time, dependable, high-performance and interoperable data exchanges between publishers and subscribers.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The standard provides interfaces to C++, C++11, C, Ada, Java, and Ruby.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The eXtensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP) is a communications protocol for message-oriented middleware based on Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Designed to be extensible, the protocol has also been used for publish-subscribe systems, signalling for VoIP, video, file transfer, gaming, Internet of Things applications such as the smart grid, and social networking services.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Unlike most instant messaging protocols, XMPP is defined in an open standard and uses an open systems approach of development and application, by which anyone may implement an XMPP service and interoperate with other organizations' implementations.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Because XMPP is an open protocol, implementations can be developed using any software license; although many server, client, and library implementations are distributed as free and open-source software, many freeware and proprietary software implementations also exist.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formed an XMPP working group in 2002 to formalize the core protocols as an IETF instant messaging and presence technology.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] The XMPP Working group produced four specifications (RFC 3920, RFC 3921, RFC 3922, RFC 3923), which were approved as Proposed Standards in 2004.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In 2011, RFC 3920 and RFC 3921 were superseded by RFC 6120 and RFC 6121 respectively, with RFC 6122 specifying the XMPP address format.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] In addition to these core protocols standardized at the IETF, the XMPP Standards Foundation (formerly Jabber Software Foundation) is active in developing open XMPP extensions.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] XMPP-based software is deployed widely across the Internet, according to the XMPP Standards Foundation, and forms the basis for the Department of Defense (DoD) Unified Capabilities Framework.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] A similar effort is with the actively evolving OpenMAMA project, which aims to provide a common API, especially to C clients.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] As of August 2012, it is mainly appropriate for distributing market-oriented data (e.g. stock quotes) over pub-sub middleware.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Message queues allow the exchange of information between distributed applications.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] A message queue can reside in memory or disk storage.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Messages stay in the queue until the time they are processed by a service consumer.
[src:nats-messaging/message-oriented-middleware] Through the message queue, the application can be implemented independently - they do not need to know each other's position, or continue to implement procedures to remove the need for waiting to receive this message.
[src:nats-messaging/nats-messaging] NATS was originally developed by Derek Collison as the messaging control plane for Cloud Foundry and was written in Ruby.
[src:nats-messaging/nats-messaging] The source code is released under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:nats-messaging/nats-messaging] The NATS server is often referred to as either 'Core NATS' or NATS with 'JetStream'.
[src:nats-messaging/nats-messaging] 'Core NATS' is the set of core NATS functionalities and qualities of service.
[src:nats-messaging/nats-messaging] 'JetStream' is the (optionally enabled) built-in persistence layer that adds streaming, queues, at-least-once and exactly-once delivery guarantees, historical data replay, decoupled flow-control and key/value store functionalities to Core NATS.
[src:nats-messaging/nats-messaging] JetStream replaced the old STAN (NATS Streaming) approach.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:nats-messaging/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
